reviewText: I don't wanna rate the course 1 star because there must be lots of effort put in there BUT it makes me extremely disappointed. - All I can learn is a few new words in Marketing. I did expect to learn a lot in this aspect but as you can see, I learned nothing. The way this course organizes titles could be accepted, but the way they impart knowledge and approach to their students is completely a failure. They use too many specialized and academic words that I consider not suitable of 'beginner level". Can you believe that I had to search for a word every 5 seconds? It wastes too much time and interrupts the lesson. I admit I'm not a academic learner, that's why I chose this course, which is for beginners. Many higher level lessons on other platforms that I've learned use much less academic words in a speech, and I obviously understand almost what they say.- Another problem is the quizzes. It was such a nightmare for me in the first graded quiz. I had to did it 4 times to pass because I really learned nothing. How can you let your learners listen to numbers of lessons which each of them is overly long with an amount of knowledge and then give them only 1 quiz review their process? At my previous course, they gave me 1-2 small quizzes each video with just 1-4 questions/quiz, but they helped me a lot! They gave me a deeper look in the main ideas so that I can absolutely approach the knowledge. I didn't find it hard to do the graded quizzes like in this course.It's hard for me to straightly complain like this but this course really needs to be fixed. Anyways, thank you for teaching me, I appreciate your effort.
Did not like the class

It was one of the worst courses i had in the whole specialization. Product & Pricing were good or can be understandable. Otherwise, i lost pace. Only the readings were my only guide throughout the course.I am disappointed as i was so excited to hit the 4Ps.
The videos were too long, as well some of the lectures. Explanations lacked clarity and lots of concepts were handled at the same time without focusing on the basics.

Hard to understand professor. When one needs to read the english subtitles to understand the english the professor is speaking, it becomes inherently difficult in an online course. Also, please kill the intro video for each course. It is completely unnecessary as the courses are labeled on the left side of the screen. Good material, but difficult to watch towards the end of the course.
week 3 and 4 so difficult  alot of information but not clear
This is the Worst module of marketing strategy. Many of the answers in the quizzes are wrong. Presenters are also not effective in delivering presentation.

Week 3 and 4 lectures are robotic - Most material taken directly from the internet. It is just a form of regurgitation of online articles from strategy consulting firms with Quiz's artificially made more difficult with cheap word plays. The lecturer for Week 3 and Week 4 should resign with immediate effect and find a job at a school for lower class students where she can continue to brag about her industry expertise without being so irritating. Definitely not IE Business School material !
The end of chapter quizzes have far too many errors to live up to Coursera's quality.
everything goes good until week3 The words were very difficult for international people. I had a hard time communicating with the teacher and unlike other courses, it was not practical at all.
The third week content was not very clearly explained by the professor and was not illustrated by examples.
I liked more the first part of the course, but less the second part
The videos of Week 3 and 4 were too long
The course provides deep insights into marketing mix but the promotion and place module requires too many "Pointers" to be remembered. Thank you

This is the worst part out of 4 in the Marketing Strategy specialisation. The topic is very important and very interesting to study, however, the form in which it was suggested was far from perfect. The 2 first parts of the marketing mix were very well presented, but when we switched to distribution channels and communication, I was lost. Lots of information, very little proper explanation - I felt overloaded and had to stop the videos every minute just to digest what has been said by the professor. I further listened to the Part 4 "Marketing Plan" and this is where I understood more about marketing mix and especially distribution channels and communication. The part of the course dedicated to distribution channels and communication should be revisited to make them easier to understand. Probably, more relevant examples and slower speed of talk by professor will help.

I liked this course, but it has some drawbacks. E.g., the timing set for reading articles was not accurate - 10 min per each even though they differ (from articles that are provided by online websites to scientific ones). Thus, it was difficult to manage time properly. Moreover, it was difficult to understand the pronunciation sometimes. Therefore, I recommend using subtitles. To sum up, I am happy I finished this course.
